KARPENTER INSTALLATION STEPS
==============================

1. Set env variables
   export CLUSTER_NAME, AWS_REGION,
   AWS_ACCOUNT_ID, KARPENTER_VERSION="1.12.0"

2. Get OIDC ID
   aws eks describe-cluster --name $CLUSTER_NAME

3. Register OIDC in IAM
   aws iam create-open-id-connect-provider

4. Create controller IAM role
   karpenter-trust-policy.json → aws iam create-role
   role: my-eks-cluster-karpenter

5. Create controller policy
   karpenter-policy.json → aws iam create-policy
   + karpenter-policy-addition.json (instance profile perms)
   → attach both to controller role

6. Create node role
   karpenter-node-trust-policy.json → aws iam create-role
   role: KarpenterNodeRole-my-eks-cluster
   → attach 4 managed policies:
      AmazonEKSWorkerNodePolicy
      AmazonEKS_CNI_Policy
      AmazonEC2ContainerRegistryReadOnly
      AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore

7. Add node role to aws-auth
   kubectl get configmap aws-auth -o yaml > aws-auth.yaml
   → add KarpenterNodeRole → kubectl apply

8. Create SQS queue
   aws sqs create-queue --queue-name my-eks-cluster

9. Tag subnets + security group
   Key=karpenter.sh/discovery
   Value=my-eks-cluster

10. Install via Helm OCI
    helm registry logout public.ecr.aws
    helm upgrade --install karpenter
    oci://public.ecr.aws/karpenter/karpenter
    --version 1.12.0
    --set memory=256Mi (not 1Gi — t3.micro)

11. Create NodePool + EC2NodeClass
    kubectl apply -f karpenter-nodepool.yaml
    instance-type: t3.micro (Free Tier only)

12. Test
    deploy 10 pods → nodes added ✅
    delete pods   → nodes removed ✅
---------------------

karpenter vs NodePool vs EC2NodeClass

1. Karpenter

Karpenter is the Kubernetes controller that:

Watches for unschedulable pods
Determines the optimal node type
Launches EC2 instances
Consolidates underutilized nodes
Terminates unused nodes

2. NodePool

A NodePool tells Karpenter:

Which workloads can use these nodes
Allowed instance types
Capacity type (Spot/On-Demand)
Architecture
Limits
Disruption policies

3. EC2NodeClass

An EC2NodeClass contains AWS-specific configuration:

AMI family
Subnets
Security groups
IAM role
EBS settings
User data
Tags
